PCA & Clustering Analysis Feature Contribution Investigation

Script Purpose

This notebook focuses on investigating the behavior and interpretability of the first two principal components (PC1 & PC2) derived from Spotify audio features, with the aim of understanding how these components contribute to genre-related structure in the dataset.

The workflow includes:

  • Hierarchical clustering (106 clusters) based on scaled audio features.
  • PCA transformation for 2D projection and visual cluster separation.
  • Detection of unintended data splits in PCA space.
  • Hypothesis testing to identify whether:
    • Highly correlated features cause the separation (FALSE)
    • Binary features are responsible (TRUE)

The binary feature "mode" was identified as the dominant factor in PC1, leading to unnatural separation. After removing "mode", the PCA visualization aligned more realistically with expected genre distributions.

Final steps include:

  • Redoing PCA and clustering without "mode".
  • Comparing pre/post-removal visualizations and feature contributions.
  • Verifying that the principal components now reflect true musical variance rather than binary-driven distortion.

Hierarchical Clustering Function

This function performs hierarchical clustering on a subset of numerical features from the dataset. It:

  • Scales features using Min-Max normalization.
  • Applies Ward's method for hierarchical clustering.
  • Uses a flat clustering method to create num_clusters (default 106).
  • Visualizes the clustering via a Seaborn clustermap.
  • Returns the clustered dataframe.

The number 106 aligns with the best-performing decision tree classifier's leaf count (97% accuracy)

In[]:
def hierarchical_clustering(df, iloc_lower, iloc_upper, num_clusters=106):
    X = df.iloc[:, iloc_lower:iloc_upper]

    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    normalized_data = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(X), columns=X.columns, index=X.index)

    Z = linkage(normalized_data, method='ward', metric='euclidean')

    num_clusters = 106
    clusters = fcluster(Z, num_clusters, criterion='maxclust')

    palette = sns.color_palette("Purples", num_clusters)
    cluster_to_color = {cluster: palette[i] for i, cluster in enumerate(np.unique(clusters))}
    row_colors = pd.Series(clusters, index=normalized_data.index).map(cluster_to_color)

    g = sns.clustermap(normalized_data,
                    row_linkage=Z,
                    col_cluster=False,
                    row_colors=row_colors,
                    cmap="magma",
                    figsize=(10, 80))

    legend_clusters = list(cluster_to_color.keys())
    legend_elements = [Patch(facecolor=cluster_to_color[cl], label=f'Cluster {cl}') for cl in legend_clusters]


    plt.gcf().legend(handles=legend_elements,
                    title='Cluster Colors',
                    loc='lower center',
                    ncol=7,
                    bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.05))

    plt.show()

    result = X.copy()
    result['cluster'] = clusters


    print(result.head())
    return result


result = hierarchical_clustering(df,6,20 )

PCA + Clustering Visualization

This function applies PCA to visualize clusters in 2D (PC1 vs PC2). It:

  • Performs hierarchical clustering.
  • Reduces data to 2D using PCA.
  • Plots a scatter plot colored by cluster IDs.
  • Adds a dynamic color-coded legend for all 106 clusters.
  • This helps investigate how genres are distributed in PC space.
In[]:
def plot_pca_clusters_with_legend(df, iloc_lower, iloc_upper, num_clusters=106):
    X = df.iloc[:, iloc_lower:iloc_upper]
    scaler = MinMaxScaler()
    normalized_data = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(X), columns=X.columns, index=X.index)

    Z = linkage(normalized_data, method='ward', metric='euclidean')
    clusters = fcluster(Z, num_clusters, criterion='maxclust')
    normalized_data['cluster'] = clusters

    pca = PCA(n_components=2)
    pca_result = pca.fit_transform(normalized_data.drop(columns='cluster'))
    pca_df = pd.DataFrame(pca_result, columns=['PC1', 'PC2'], index=X.index)
    pca_df['cluster'] = clusters

    palette = sns.color_palette("Purples", num_clusters)

    fig, (ax_main, ax_legend) = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(14, 12), gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [4, 1]})

    sns.scatterplot(data=pca_df, x='PC1', y='PC2', hue='cluster', palette=palette, legend=False, ax=ax_main)
    ax_main.set_title("PCA Projection of Hierarchical Clusters")
    ax_main.set_xlabel("Principal Component 1")
    ax_main.set_ylabel("Principal Component 2")
    ax_main.grid(True)

    ax_legend.axis('off')
    n_cols = 6
    n_rows = -(-num_clusters // n_cols)  

    x_spacing = 1.0 / n_cols
    y_spacing = 1.0 / (n_rows + 1)

    for i in range(num_clusters):
        col = i % n_cols
        row = i // n_cols
        x = col * x_spacing
        y = 1 - (row + 1) * y_spacing

        color_patch = mpatches.Rectangle((x, y), 0.02, 0.04, transform=ax_legend.transAxes,
                                         facecolor=palette[i], edgecolor='black')
        ax_legend.add_patch(color_patch)
        ax_legend.text(x + 0.025, y + 0.01, f'Cluster {i + 1}', transform=ax_legend.transAxes,
                       fontsize=8, va='center')


    plt.figtext(0.5, 0.02, "Each cluster is represented by a unique shade of purple. The color mapping helps visually identify which samples belong to which clusters.",
                ha='center', fontsize=10)

    plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.04, 1, 1])
    plt.show()

    return pca_df


pca_df =plot_pca_clusters_with_legend(df,6,20)

Merge Clustering and PCA Results

This block merges PCA results with hierarchical cluster labels for deeper analysis. It also computes a signed Euclidean distance from a decision boundary in the PCA space, allowing us to segment data visually into two groups based on PC1.

In[]:
df_cluster_PCA = pd.merge(result, pca_df, left_index=True, right_index=True)
df_cluster_PCA.drop(columns=["cluster_y"], inplace=True)
df_cluster_PCA.reset_index(inplace=True)

pc1 = df_cluster_PCA["PC1"].tolist()
pc2 = df_cluster_PCA["PC2"].tolist()

def get_pca_distance_with_x_sign(x, y, boundary_x=-0.25, boundary_y=0):
    distance = np.sqrt((x - boundary_x)**2 + (y - boundary_y)**2)
    return distance if x > boundary_x else -distance

pc_distances = [get_pca_distance_with_x_sign(x, y) for x, y in zip(pc1, pc2)]
df_cluster_PCA["PCA_EuclidianDist(Xsign)"] = pc_distances

def add_first_boundary_group(df, distance_column="PCA_EuclidianDist(Xsign)"):
    df["1th_Boundary"] = df[distance_column].apply(lambda x: -1 if x < 0 else 1)
    return df

df_cluster_PCA_gp = add_first_boundary_group(df_cluster_PCA)
df_cluster_PCA_gp = pd.merge(df["track_genre"], df_cluster_PCA_gp, left_index=True, right_index=True)

groupA = df_cluster_PCA_gp[df_cluster_PCA_gp["1th_Boundary"] == -1]
groupB = df_cluster_PCA_gp[df_cluster_PCA_gp["1th_Boundary"] == 1]

Plot Feature Comparisons (Group A vs B)

This function compares selected audio features between the two PCA-segmented groups (Group A and Group B) using scatter plots. It visualizes how features like acousticness, energy, danceability, valence differ between the PCA hemispheres.

In[]:
def plot_feature_comparisons(groupA, groupB, comparisons, groupA_label='Group A', groupB_label='Group B'):
    for x_feat, y_feat in comparisons:
        plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
        plt.scatter(groupA[x_feat], groupA[y_feat], alpha=0.6, label=groupA_label)
        plt.scatter(groupB[x_feat], groupB[y_feat], alpha=0.6, label=groupB_label)
        plt.xlabel(x_feat)
        plt.ylabel(y_feat)
        plt.title(f"{x_feat} vs {y_feat}")
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

comparisons = [("acousticness", "energy"), ( "energy", "loudness"), ("danceability","valence" )]
plot_feature_comparisons(groupA,groupB,comparisons)

PCA Feature Contribution Analysis

This function shows the importance (loadings) of each feature to PC1 and PC2. It's essential to understand what features drive the separation in PCA space. In this investigation, the feature "mode" was dominant and binary, misleading PCA interpretation.

In[]:
def pca_feature_contributions(df, iloc_lower, iloc_upper, n_components=2, sort_by='PC1'):
    features = df.iloc[:, iloc_lower:iloc_upper]
    scaled = MinMaxScaler().fit_transform(features)
    pca = PCA(n_components=n_components)
    pca.fit(scaled)
    loadings = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_.T, columns=[f'PC{i+1}' for i in range(n_components)], index=features.columns)
    return loadings.sort_values(by=sort_by, ascending=False)

pca_f = pca_feature_contributions(df,6,20)

Drop Binary Feature "mode"
